			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2009</a> paper:</span><br><i>An Automated Process for Implementing Multilevel Domain Models</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/FrédéricMallet.html">Frédéric Mallet</a>, <a href="../profile/FrançoisLagarde.html">François Lagarde</a>, <a href="../profile/CharlesAndré.html">Charles André</a>, <a href="../profile/SébastienGérard.html">Sébastien Gérard</a>, <a href="../profile/FrançoisTerrier.html">François Terrier</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_22">10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_22</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> Multilevel modeling is fundamentally about meta-level language structure and metametamodel concerns.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The contribution is an automated process, i.e., tooling support for implementing such models.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagL">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> It affects language design choices for multilevel domain modeling constructs and their instantiation rules.
</li></ul></li></ul>
